## 1. Prepare Modeling Data

We apply a `log1p()` transformation to `Global_Sales` to address right-skew before modeling.
We also scale `User_Score` from 0–10 to 0–100 to match `Critic_Score`.
Rows missing any key predictor are dropped (complete-case analysis).

```{r prep}
df <- run_pipeline()

# Feature engineering
df <- df %>%
  mutate(
    log_Global_Sales = log1p(Global_Sales),
    User_Score_100   = User_Score * 10,
    Genre            = as.factor(Genre),
    Rating           = as.factor(Rating),
    Platform         = as.factor(Platform)
  )

# Collapse rare ESRB ratings
standard_ratings <- c("E", "E10+", "T", "M")
df <- df %>%
  mutate(Rating = if_else(Rating %in% standard_ratings, as.character(Rating), "Other"),
         Rating = as.factor(Rating))

# Model dataset: complete cases for all key predictors
model_df <- df %>%
  filter(
    !is.na(Critic_Score),
    !is.na(User_Score_100),
    !is.na(Rating)
  )

cat("Rows available for modeling:", nrow(model_df), "\n")
cat("log_Global_Sales skew:", round(moments::skewness(model_df$log_Global_Sales), 3), "\n")
```

---

## 2. Full Model

We include all variables we believe are relevant to predicting global sales:

- `Critic_Score` — professional review scores from Metacritic
- `User_Score_100` — user review scores scaled to 0–100
- `Year_of_Release` — captures industry wide trends over time
- `Genre` — categorical, 12 levels
- `Rating` — ESRB rating, captures target audience

We exclude `Name`, `Developer`, `Publisher` (too many factor levels, would overfit),
and regional sales (`NA_Sales`, `EU_Sales`, `JP_Sales`, `Other_Sales`) since they are
components of `Global_Sales`, including them would be data leakage.

```{r full-model}
full_model <- lm(
  log_Global_Sales ~ Critic_Score + User_Score_100 + Year_of_Release + Genre + Rating,
  data = model_df
)

summary(full_model)
```

### Model Fit

```{r full-model-fit}
cat("R-squared:     ", round(summary(full_model)$r.squared,     4), "\n")
cat("Adj R-squared: ", round(summary(full_model)$adj.r.squared, 4), "\n")
cat("Residual SE:   ", round(summary(full_model)$sigma,         4), "\n")
cat("F-statistic p: ", round(pf(summary(full_model)$fstatistic[1],
                                summary(full_model)$fstatistic[2],
                                summary(full_model)$fstatistic[3],
                                lower.tail = FALSE), 6), "\n")
```

### Coefficient Table

```{r full-model-coefs}
coef_df <- as.data.frame(summary(full_model)$coefficients)
coef_df$Significant <- ifelse(coef_df[,4] < 0.05, "Yes", "No")
kable(round(coef_df[,1:4], 5) %>% cbind(Significant = coef_df$Significant),
      caption = "Full Model Coefficients")
```

---

## 3. Assumption Diagnostics

### 3a. Residuals vs Fitted

```{r diag-1, fig.height=4}
plot(fitted(full_model), resid(full_model),
     col = "grey", pch = 20,
     xlab = "Fitted", ylab = "Residuals",
     main = "Residuals vs Fitted — Full Model")
abline(h = 0, col = "darkorange", lwd = 2)
```

### 3b. Breusch-Pagan Test (Homoscedasticity)

```{r bp-test}
bptest(full_model)
```

> A significant p-value indicates heteroscedasticity — the variance of residuals is not constant across fitted values. This is common with sales data even after log-transforming.

### 3c. Normal Q-Q Plot

```{r diag-qq}
qqnorm(resid(full_model), main = "Normal Q-Q Plot Full Model", col = "darkgrey")
qqline(resid(full_model), col = "dodgerblue", lwd = 2)
```

### 3d. Residual Histogram

```{r diag-hist, fig.height=4}
hist(resid(full_model),
     main   = "Histogram of Residuals Full Model",
     xlab   = "Residuals",
     col    = "darkorange",
     border = "dodgerblue",
     breaks = 30)
```

> **Assumption Summary:**
> - **Linearity:** Check residuals vs fitted — should show no clear pattern.
> - **Normality:** Q-Q plot and histogram — residuals should follow a normal distribution.
> - **Homoscedasticity:** BP test — ideally non significant.
> - **Independence:** Assumed given the dataset structure (one row per game platform).

